passages.text: As we approach the last trading day (LTD) for the front contracts of JBU5 and JJAU5 on September 12, we anticipate that the market's near- term focus will be predominantly on rollover transactions. This analysis is based on data available up to the market close on August 28.
What sets this report apart from previous ones is the inclusion of an analysis for mini 20- year JGB futures (JJA), driven by the recent increase in open interest (OI) of JJA (Figure 1).
Figure 1: What sets this report apart from previous ones is the inclusion of a rollover outlook for mini 20-year JGB futures (JJA)

Recently, JBU5/JBZ5 has been trading within a narrow range (Figure 2). Compared to previous rollovers, the current rollover activity has been notably sluggish (Figure 3).
Figure 2: Recently, JBU5/JBZ5 has been trading within a narrow range...
Source:JPX,J.P.Morgan.
Figure 3: ...and compared to previous rollovers, the current rollover activity has been notably sluggish
Source:JPX,J.P.Morgan.

The CTD bonds for JBU5 and JBZ5 are JB368 and JB369, respectively. The difference in maturity between these front and back contracts leads to a variation in the futures DV01. Specifically, a 1bp parallel shift in the yield curve results in a 0.161 sen sensitivity of the calendar spread. The DV01 neutral hedge ratio between the two contracts is 1000:983.

Nebasis: We expect a neutral biasTheory, the net basis should converge to zero as we approach the LTD, but this is often not the case for the back contract. Despite this, we can use net basis analysis to estimate the theoretical value of the calendar spread (Figure 4).

For the front contract (JBU5), we estimated the T/N SC repo rate for JB368 (the first CTD) to be around 43bp as of August 28. Assuming this rate remains flat between now and the LTD of the contract, this results in a front net basis of \(+1.3\) sen in bond price terms, indicating a 2.0 bullish/widening bias on the calendar spread.

For the back contract (JBZ5), we estimated the T/N SC repo rate for JB369 (the first CTD) to be around 27bp as of August 28. Assuming this rate also remains flat between now and the LTD of the contract, this results in a front net basis of - 5.2 sen in bond price terms, suggesting a 7.5 sen bullish/widening bias on the calendar spread.

Our mechanical net basis analysis indicates that the theoretical value of the calendar spread as of August 28 was 110.5 sen, which was 9.5 sen higher than the actual market close of 101.0 sen. However, we believe that the repo rate for the back contract is low, given the possibility of an October hike, which suggests a bearish/narrowing bias. Taking this into account, we anticipate an overall neutral bias on the calendar spread.
Figure 4: We anticipate an overall neutral bias on the calendar spread

Both JB368 and JB369 were issued after the commencement of QQE2, making them generally scarce in the market. We estimate that the BoJ held around \(84\%\) of JB368 and JB369 as of August 20 (Figure 9). We anticipate that the scarcity of CTDs will exert a neutral bias on the calendar spread.

The CTD spread between JB369 and JB368 closed at around 2.5bp on August 28 (Figure 10). Over the past six months, this spread has traded between around 2.0- 3.5bp. We believe there is a higher likelihood of the CTD spread remaining around 2.5bp, which should exert a neutral impact on the calendar spread.
Figure 9: We anticipate that the scarcity of CTDs will exert a neutral bias on the calendar spread
Source:Bloomberg Finance L.P.,BoJ,J.P.Morgan.
Figure 10: We believe there is a higher likelihood of the CTD spread remaining around 2.5bp

We anticipate that the JBUS/JBZ5 calendar spread will follow the recent rollover pattern. As we near the peak of rollover activity, typically from around LTD- 3, the calendar spread is expected to rise and reach the upper bound of our anticipated range. After the peak, we project the spread to decline to around the lower end of the range. Overall, we forecast the trading range of the calendar spread to be between 96 and 106 sen (closed at 101 sen on August 28) (Figure 11).
Figure 11: We anticipate that the JBU5/JBZ5 calendar spread will follow the recent rollover pattern and forecast the trading range of the calendar spread to be between 96 and 106 sen

FactorNoteExpected ImpactFront net basis+2.0 sen in futures term (bullish/widening bias)NeutralBack net basis-7.5 sen in futures term (bullish/widening bias), but repo rate seems too low, given the possibility of an October hikePositioningWe believe that CTAs currently hold relatively large short positions. Moreover, we estimate that investment trusts and trust banks also hold large net short positions. Conversely, we think proprietary accounts such as dealers are net long. Overall, we believe the current positioning landscape mirrors the previous rollover. We anticipate that the calendar spread will rise as we approach the peak of rollover activity (typically from around LTD-3), since investors such as CTAs and bear funds, who cannot settle by physical delivery, will roll. After this peak, we expect the spread to decline as proprietary accounts that can handle physical delivery will roll, and any remaining long rollovers take place.Bullish/widening into the peak rollover and then bearish/narrowing into the LTDCTD scarcityThe BoJ holds 84% of JB368 and JB369.NeutralCTD spreadWe believe there is a higher likelihood of the CTD spread remaining around 2.5bp.NeutralDeltaEven if there is a 6bp parallel shift of the JGB curve, the calendar spread would only widen by less than 1 sen.NeutralExpected range96 sen to 106 sen (as of the August 28 close = 101 sen)

For the first time in many years, trading activity in JJA is picking up, with OI for the front contract now standing around 6,150 contracts (Figure 12). The spread has been mostly range- bound, but there were rollovers of 500 and 100 contracts on August 26 and 28, respectively (Figure 13).
Figure 12: For the first time in many years, trading activity in JJA is picking up
Source:JPX,J.P.Morgan.
Figure 13: Spread has been mostly range-bound, but there were rollovers of 500 and 100 contracts on August 26 and 28, respectively JJAU5/JJAZ5 rollover over the past 14 business days (yen; contracts)
Source:JPX,J.P.Morgan.
The CTD bonds for JJAUS and JJAZS are JL192 and JL193, respectively.

For the front contract (JJAUS), we estimated the T/N SC repo rate for JL192 (the first CTD) to be around 45bp as of August 28 (Figure 14). Assuming this rate remains flat between now and the LTD of the contract, this results in a front net basis of - 6.3 sen in bond price terms, indicating a 6.9 sen bearish/narrowing bias on the calendar spread.

For the back contract (JJAZ5), we estimated the T/N SC repo rate for JL193 (the first CTD) to be around 45bp as of August 28. Assuming this rate also remains flat between now and the LTD of the contract, this results in a front net basis of - 0.3 sen in bond price terms, suggesting a - 0.3 sen bullish/widening bias on the calendar spread. However, we believe that the repo rate for the back contract is low, given the possibility of an October rate hike.

Our mechanical net basis analysis indicates that the theoretical value of the calendar spread as of August 28 was 86.4 sen, which was 6.6 sen lower than the actual market close of 93.0 sen. Overall, we anticipate a bearish/narrowing bias on the calendar spread.
Figure 14: Our net basis analysis indicates a bearish/narrowing bias

Analyzing JPX's weekly transaction data, we observe that trading activity for JJA is predominantly concentrated among proprietary accounts, which likely represents the activity of dealers and domestic real money accounts (Figure 15). In contrast, foreign investors, who are the main participants in 10-year JGB futures, have a limited presence (Figure 16). This positioning landscape indicates that there are likely a limited number of players who must or choose to roll due to their restrictions and/or operational reasons.

Given the uncertainty surrounding JJA rollovers, investors may opt to unwind positions before the LTD. Nonetheless, we anticipate that some investors will choose to roll.Considering our estimate that proprietary accounts are the major players and hold a net short position, we expect overall positioning to exert a bullish/widening bias on the calendar spread.
Figure 15: We observe that trading activity for JJA is predominantly concentrated among proprietary accounts, which likely represents the activity of dealers and domestic real money accounts
Proprietary accounts' estimated net position: Gross purchases and sales (left axis) vs. estimated net positioning (right axis) (latest as of August 22) (number of contracts)
Source:JPX,J.P.Morgan.
Figure 16: Foreign investors have a limited presence
Source:JPX,J.P.Morgan.
We estimate the BoJ held \(2.3\%\) of JL192 and \(0.8\%\) of JL193 as of August 20 (Figure 17). Although the free float is plentiful, investors are unlikely to choose physical delivery.

The CTD spread between JL192 and JL193 closed at around 1.6bp on August 28 (Figure 18). Over the past month, this spread has traded between around 1.0- 1.5bp. We believe there is a higher likelihood of the CTD spread remaining around 1.5bp, which should have a neutral impact on the calendar spread.
Separately, while it is a consideration for the future, we believe that a delivery option will likely gain importance for JJA moving forward.
Figure 17: Although the free float of CTDs is plentiful, we do not believe that investors will choose physical delivery

Overall, our assessment of positioning indicates a bullish/widening bias on the spread. However, we believe that positioning considerations are already reflected in the price, as suggested by our net basis analysis. We forecast the trading range of the calendar spread to be between 82 and 99 sen (closed at 93 sen on August 28) (Figure 19).
